audioContentItems.fileTranscript: Today we’re turning quoting chaos into quoting confidence—because pricing shouldn’t feel like rocket science!
Here are a few tips for how to navigate throughout this Sym. Click the arrow when you’re ready to continue.
The Quote Tool is a new tab available within a prospect or client record.
Quote Parameter fields will auto populate with the available profile information of that record.
Let’s go check it out in action in my favorite place, Salesforce!
Great job getting a quote for Tim and his granddaughter.
What if you have a caller on the line looking for a quote and they don’t have a Salesforce profile?
There’s a quote tool for that situation too, using the DSC Quote Tool located at the bottom left of your Salesforce task bar.
You’re really getting the hang of this quote tool!
I wanted to bring your attention to a few more smart features of the Quote Tool.
These features help make it easier for you to ensure you are providing accurate quotes on every call!
What did we learn today? Take a moment to review some of the key learnings from this sym.
Click the lightbulb when you are ready to continue.
Now that you’ve learned the Salesforce Quote Tool, go hit the phones and quote like a pro—fast, fearless, and fabulously accurate!

settings.text: We have Tim Allen on the line and we’ve done our discovery to find out that the product that meets his needs will likely be around a $15,000 UCSL policy as long as it fits in his budget of $120 a month. Click the quote tool tab to give him a quote.
The quote tool pulled in the state, gender, and age from his profile into the quote parameters.
We are going to quote UCSL1, so we can keep that. Change the face amount to $15,000.
Click Get Quote
Great work! A quote card has appeared, letting you know the monthly price for this policy is $141.10.

Tim said his budget for this policy was around $120 and he absolutely can not go over that. Let’s see if we can find him something in his budget. Click on the face amount drop down in the quote card to see what other options we have.

Notice how the menu here shows the face amount and price. We can see that the $12,000 policy is $113.08. This policy will offer the most coverage while staying within Tim's monthly budget of $120/month.
Great! $12,000 of coverage is under his budget, $113.08.

Great! Now, he tells you that the reason he didn’t want to go over $120 for himself is that he wants to put $30 towards getting his 8-year-old granddaughter a policy for as high as he can at that price. He says she is also in Colorado. Type in the age, 8.
Change the Gender to Female.
Choose CWL as the product.
Finally, let’s see how much it would cost him to get the maximum amount of coverage for his granddaughter, $50,000.
Great news! The maximum amount of coverage for his granddaughter is just $23.17. He confirms he wants to purchase the $50,000 CWL. These two policies bring his monthly total right now to $136.25.

You let Tim know the new total and that he could go a little higher with his own coverage and still stay under the $150 total budget. He could add about $14 and still be around his budget. Let’s see what he has for options to increase his coverage. Click on the Face Amount drop down in the UCSL1 quote card.
Let’s check what his total is with a face Amount of $13,000.

You let him know that adding that extra $1,000 of coverage keeps him under $150 and he says he's ready to buy both! Navigate back to the sales tab to disposition the sale and open the first application.
That concludes the first part of the simulation.

If you have a caller on the line who will not let you create an account until they have gotten a quote, you can still use the standalone quote tool. Click on the tool in the bottom left of your screen.

You have Wilma on the line, a 68-year-old woman living in Iowa. She got a mailer for the CHS product and is interested in the price for the $200 Daily Room Benefit plan. She doesn’t want to give you any information unless she decides to buy. Change the state to Iowa.
Type in the age, 68.
Change the Gender to female.
Change the Product to CHS10.
Choose the $200 Daily Room Benefit.
As you can see, a quote for Wilma would be $53.81.
This concludes the simulation.
